post_text:
Vacancy Posting for Seminole Public Schools

Position: Full-time Registered School Nurse

Position Start Date: Immediate

Minimum Qualifications (Knowledge, Skills and/or Abilities Required):

• Registered Nurse with valid license issued by the Oklahoma Board of Nurse Registration and Nursing Education.

• Must attain a certification as a School Nurse through the Oklahoma State Department of Education.

• Clinical experience in one or more of the following areas desired: Pediatric Nursing, Medical-Surgical Nursing, Emergency/Trauma Nursing or Public Health/Community Health Nursing

If interested in this position, please email awillmett@sps.k12.ok.us

post_text: August 21 News Release
text: August 21 News Release

post_text:
Parents of Virtual or Distance Learning Students:
Good news – your student WILL be able to continue to receive meals at no cost to you! We will give one full week’s worth of meals at a time for each student enrolled in either Virtual or Distance Learning.

Beginning Monday, August 24, you will need to contact us each week to place your order for the following week. Orders need to be received no later than 2:00 pm on Wednesday of each week in order to give our cafeteria time to purchase, prepare and package those meals. Meals will then be able to be picked up every Monday morning from 8:30 – 9:30 am at the Seminole Middle School Cafeteria.

***EMAIL your orders to meals@sps.k12.ok.us (preferred) OR CALL them in to 405-382-5085 X 208***

post_text: Seminole Public Schools has chosen to delay the start of the 2020 school year. The new first day of school will be August 21st. We have been working diligently to prepare our buildings, facilities, and grounds for the upcoming year. After the update from the Oklahoma State Board of Education meeting, we feel that it is necessary to delay our start in an effort to ensure that we can provide the safest, most educationally appropriate environment for all students and staff. We appreciate your patience and understanding and we look forward to the day that we can welcome all of our Chieftains back to school!

We appreciate your patience and understanding and we look forward to the day that we can welcome all of our Chieftains back to school!

post_text: This was posted today by the Seminole County Assessor. Please share this post.
shared_text:
Seminole County Assessor's Office
August 13, 2019 at 2:05 PM ·

Where do my property tax dollars go?

Each dollar of your ad valorem tax, on the statewide average, is apportioned about 68% for common schools, 13% career tech, 16% county, with the remaining 3% percent apportioned to other publicly supported projects as authorized by the voters.

When a School District passes a bond, it is repaid by the owners of property located within that School District, NOT the entire County. Below is a map of the School Districts in Seminole County.

post_text: Mrs. Stuteville's class is the first to win the Northwood Attendance Challenge for the 2015-2016 school year. They had 98.12% attendance for the months of August and September. That impressive effort earned them lunch at S&L Diner with their teacher and the principal. The students said, "We are going to win next time too!" Thank you to the S&L Diner staff for taking such good care of our students.

post_text: The SSC Belles basketball team met the 6th grade girls today during their PE time. Coach Rita Schell spoke to 6th graders about dedication, effort and attitude. She explained how basketball could actually pay for all their college if they worked hard toward that goal. The Belles also demonstrated several of their drills and modeled encouragement for everyone whether they made or missed their shots.

Reif, and Law Day Co-Chairmen, Judge Tim Olsen and Jack Cadenhead.

post_text: Wilson Elementary is participating in "Pennies for Patients". The students are collecting money for children diagnosed with cancer. We had a special guest speaker from the Leukemia & Lymphoma Society who helped educate the kids on blood cancers through skits using students and props. Dawn Thornton also explained how the program works. The class that raises the most money wins a pizza party. The school's goal is $1500. The program will run through Jan. 30th. Parents, family, and friends can also go online to donate at http://ok.sy.llsevent.org/woodrowwilsonelementary and scroll all the way down the page to "Woodrow Wilson Elementary School". Under the DONATE NOW tab you can click the link to donate to a specific teacher's classroom and it will count towards their classroom total.

post_text: At approximately 1:30, Seminole Schools' police officer, William Williams, was notified of an active shooter in the New Lima vicinity. At 2:15, Officer Williams received information from the Seminole Police Department that the threat was contained, and the lockdown was removed.

post_text: Northwood opened the week with Operation Green Pride at their weekly Chieftain Chat. SHS cheer, pom, band and players treated the students to an all out Green and White pep assembly this morning. Cheers, songs, dances and a pep talk from Coach Shawn Snyder left the young Chieftains inspired to demonstrate their Green Pride in every endeavor. Go Big Green!

post_text: Chase Conner, Daylan Saxon and Turner Morgan are proud of the support their fellow Cowboy fans are showing for the Northwood Bedlam Food Drive. The food drive continues through November 21. Anyone wishing to contribute is welcome to drop off canned goods and add them to their favorite Oklahoma team's pile. Sooners are in the lead as of today, so we need the faithful Pokes to give, give, give!

post_text: CHIEFTAINS WIN AGAIN! The playoff road continues for another week. The Green Pride train will leave the station on Tuesday at Northwood's Chieftain Chat at 8:15 with a mini pep assembly for the students in the Northwood gym. SHS is helping us begin new traditions as we teach the students all about Green Pride at Northwood. All are welcome to join us! CONGRATULATIONS CHIEFTAINS!!

post_text: The students at BLS honored those who have served our country on Veteran's Day. Students greeted veterans giving them programs and flag pins. They were escorted down the hallway as students waved flags and cheered. They were treated to a performance of "My Country Tis of Thee", "Grand Old Flag", and "This Land is Your Land".

post_text: It was a full house as Northwood honored the five branches of the Armed Forces on Veteran's Day. Students were decked out in red, white, and blue and sang songs, read poems, and gave thanks to our Veterans!
